<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <style>
        .box-model-demo {
            /* 1. Content: The width and height of the actual stuff inside */
            width: 300px;
            background-color: lightblue;

            /* 2. Padding: Space INSIDE the border (between text and border) */
            padding: 30px;

            /* 3. Border: The line wrapping around the padding and content */
            border: 10px solid navy;

            /* 4. Margin: Space OUTSIDE the border (pushes other elements away) */
            margin: 50px;

            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            text-align: center;
        }

        .label { font-weight: bold; color: navy; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <h2>Understanding the CSS Box Model</h2>

    <div class="box-model-demo">
        <span class="label">I am the Content</span>
        <p>Everything you see in this light blue area is inside the <b>Padding</b>. 
           The thick dark line is the <b>Border</b>, and the empty white space 
           outside the box is the <b>Margin</b>.</p>
    </div>

    <p style="background-color: #eee;">
        This text is pushed away because of the <b>Margin</b> of the box above.
    </p>

</body>
</html>
